title: For Sale:  LWRC ICDI Complete Upper
postcontent: Do you want one of those fancy LWRC carbines with the spiral-fluted barrel... but just not quite enough to be willing to part with $1400 - 1700 dollars for it? Well, now if you have it for far less, if you have any halfway decent lower receiver lying around (or plan to). I have for sale a complete direct gas upper from LWRC, chambered in 5.56 NATO, lightly used and well cared for. Just drop it on and you're good to go. This one has a 16" cold hammer forged heavy barrel, coated with LWRC's proprietary NiCorr treatment, and spiral-fluted for strength and lightness. (This also looks really good, and makes you feel like the coolest dude on the firing line. ) It's got a 1:7 twist to stabilize just about anything, and it's free floated away from the handguard for eliminate barrel harmonics. All this accuracy stuff they did really works, too. This upper has shot ("theoretically can shoot", but HAS shot), consistent 1/2 MOA groups at 100 meters, and some 2 MOA groups at 600 meters, this last not with match grade ammo, not even with heavy stuff, but 55 grain cheap PMC ammo. That means 2 MOA even after the round goes transsonic. Tough to beat that. The bolt carrier group has LWRC's proprietary nickel treatment. This is good stuff... it loses its silvery shine quite soon, but it stays really smooth and slippery, and just runs with whatever you throw at it. Here's a list of every malfunction I have ever had with this upper: { } Basically, this is half of the best rifle I have ever owned. So why sell it? Because I bought the same thing in a gas piston version, which is much easier to clean. Frankly, this thing will run super dirty, and lubed with nothing but the tears of liberal politicians, but I like clean rifles, and so I've made the switch, and I'm selling off everything DI that I own. title: For Sale:  Remington Eddystone Enfield P14 WI C&R
postcontent: All-original and matching P14 Eddystone Enfield. This rifle was manufactured in the first year of the model's production and is a rare example of a correct, all-original Pattern-14 Enfield. A very early rifle, this 5-digit serial numbered P14 has seen neither refinish nor restoration. Lacking an import mark, all maker coded parts are marked 'E' and the only serialized components-the bolt handle and receiver-are matching. Having escaped Wheedon conversion, the gun retains its original volley sights-with the front sight being unmarred and the very rare rear volley sight in place. Broad Arrow marked on the buttstock, there is also what may be a Second World War homeguard cartouche. No rust or deep pitting are present and all markings are correct, legible and matching. The furniture shows clear markings, a unit disk and cartouche on the buttstock. Mechanically, the rifle appears flawless and the bore is very good having strong, sharp rifling beneath residue and lint. Would Ship!

title: For Sale:  FEG P9RK 9mm
postcontent: This beautiful 9 mm pistol is in like-new condition. It is not a Hi Power, but it looks like one. This FEG P9RK double-action semi-automatic pistol comes with a 14 and a 10 round magazine, and factory walnut grips, all for $325. It would make a perfect duty pistol, or a protective house gun.Here is a little history on the P9RK pistol:The FEG P9RK is the short-barrel version of the P9R pistol. Both guns are made in Hungary by the FEGARMY Arms factory. The P9RK uses the modified P9 frame and action, with a Smith & Wesson double-action trigger system. The P9RK is a short recoil operated, locked breech pistol. The barrel is operated using a Browning cam system, and is locked to the slide by three locking lugs on the top of the barrel, which fit into mated recesses on the inside of the slide, just ahead of the ejection port. Frame and slide are made from carbon steel and have a blued finish. The Double Action trigger system with external hammer has a slide-mounted safety lever, which also works as a de-cocker when safety is engaged. The front sight is permanently fixed to the slide, while rear sight is dovetailed. Just contact me if you have any questions.
